{
  "schema_name": "eywa_node_response",
  "schema_version": "v1",
  "orchestration_decision": "delegate",
  "decision_notes": "The problem requires reconstructing a sequence of merge operations. This is essentially a tree reconstruction problem where we must determine the order in which siblings were merged to form the final structure. This involves analyzing the parent-child relationships and the order of siblings in the final tree.",
  "helpers": [
    {
      "label": "tree_structure_analyzer",
      "instructions": "Parse the input representing the initial tree and the final tree. Represent both as adjacency lists or parent-child mappings. Identify the set of nodes that are 'merged' (nodes that exist in the initial tree but are absent in the final tree) and the specific parent-child relationships that were altered."
    },
    {
      "label": "merge_dependency_mapper",
      "instructions": "For each node in the final tree, identify its children. Compare these children to the children of the corresponding node in the initial tree. Determine which groups of siblings in the initial tree were merged into a single child in the final tree. Map these 'merge groups' to their respective parents."
    },
    {
      "label": "operation_sequencer",
      "instructions": "Given the merge groups, determine a valid topological order for the operations. A merge operation on siblings of node $u$ must occur before any operation that involves the resulting merged node as a child of another merge, or before any operation on its ancestors if the structure dictates. Specifically, identify the order of merges such that each operation transforms a set of siblings into a single node, respecting the tree hierarchy from leaves up to the root."
    }
  ],
  "synthesis_brief": "Combine the results by: 1. Using the tree_structure_analyzer to identify which nodes were merged. 2. Using the merge_dependency_mapper to group initial siblings into the specific 'merge events' that created the final tree's children. 3. Using the operation_sequencer to order these events. The final answer is the sequence of merge operations (identifying the parent and the range/set of siblings being merged) that reconstructs the final tree from the initial one."
}
```

